<div class="header">
  <div class="header-content">
    <div class="tag">Compiled by Gemini 3.1</div>
    <h1>3M Company (MMM)<br/>Intrinsic Value</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A transparent, two-stage discounted cash flow valuation of 3M Company — using FY2025 actuals, disclosed assumptions, and one final number.</p>
    <p class="date">Updated March 18, 2026 · Data: FY2025 10-K</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="container">
  <!-- ═══ THE VERDICT ═══ -->
  <div class="verdict-card">
    <div class="verdict-label">Estimated Intrinsic Value Per Share</div>
    <div class="verdict-price">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</div>
    <div class="verdict-vs">vs. market price of ${currentPrice.toFixed(2)} ({marginOfSafety}%)</div>
    <div class="verdict-badge" style={`background: ${verdictColor}22; color: ${verdictColor}; border: 1px solid ${verdictColor}44;`}>
      {verdictText}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ KEY METRICS ═══ -->
  <div class="stats-row">
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$24.9B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">FY2025 Revenue</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$1.4B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Free Cash Flow</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">$6.00</div>
      <div class="stat-label">EPS (Diluted)</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">18.6%</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Operating Margin</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">-${(Math.abs(netCash) / 1000).toFixed(1)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Net Cash</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model — the gold standard of intrinsic valuation. No multiples, no comparables, no vibes. Just future cash flows discounted to today.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with actual Free Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>3M generated <strong>$1.4 billion</strong> in free cash flow in FY2025. This is operating cash flow minus capital expenditures. This is real cash the business produces after paying for everything necessary to maintain operations.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We model FCF growing at <strong>5% per year</strong> for 5 years. Following a challenging restructuring period and the spinoff of Solventum, this represents a modest recovery and stabilization of 3M's core industrial and consumer operations.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume FCF grows at <strong>2.0% forever</strong>. This is a conservative estimate for a mature industrial conglomerate, slightly trailing long-term nominal GDP growth to reflect a highly competitive global manufacturing landscape.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>All future cash flows are discounted at <strong>9%</strong>. This represents our required return to hold 3M equity, factoring in a 4.18% risk-free rate and an appropriate equity risk premium for an established, slow-growth blue-chip with ongoing legal liabilities.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Add net cash, divide by shares</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value + Net Cash ($-6.67B) = Equity Value. Since 3M holds more debt than cash, this significantly reduces the equity value. Divide by shares outstanding (537.4M) for the per-share intrinsic value.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>A DCF is only as good as its inputs. We're making exactly <strong>three</strong> judgment calls — everything else is math. Here's what we chose and why.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">5%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        3M is undergoing an operational turnaround. Revenue and FCF growth have been volatile due to legal settlements (PFAS, Combat Arms) and the Solventum healthcare spin-off. We expect a modest recovery as restructuring benefits take hold. 5% reflects stability rather than rapid acceleration for a legacy industrial conglomerate.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">9%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        10Y Treasury: 4.18%. As a mature, dividend-paying company, 3M has a lower beta than tech stocks but carries idiosyncratic legal and regulatory risks. A 9% discount rate represents a fair required return for an investor holding a slow-growth legacy asset with complex liabilities.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">2.0%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Long-term nominal GDP growth is typically around 3%. We apply a 2.0% terminal rate for 3M. An industrial conglomerate with significant legacy operations and strong global competition is unlikely to outpace broader economic growth indefinitely. 2.0% aligns with mature inflation-adjusted stability.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ FCF PROJECTIONS TABLE ═══ -->
  <h2>Projected Free Cash Flows</h2>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
          <th>FCF ($M)</th>
          <th>PV Factor</th>
          <th>Present Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Base (FY2025)</td>
          <td>${fcf2025.toLocaleString()}</td>
          <td>—</td>
          <td>—</td>
        </tr>
        {projectedFCF.map(p => (
          <tr>
            <td>Year {p.year} ({2025 + p.year})</td>
            <td>${p.fcf.toLocaleString()}</td>
            <td>{p.pvFactor.toFixed(4)}</td>
            <td>${p.pvFCF.toLocaleString()}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td colspan="3">Sum of Phase 1 PV</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ TERMINAL VALUE ═══ -->
  <h3>Terminal Value</h3>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Component</th>
          <th>Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Year 6 FCF (Year 5 × 1.020)</td>
          <td>${Math.round(fcfYear6).toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Terminal Value (FCF₆ ÷ (9% − 2.0%))</td>
          <td>${terminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td>PV of Terminal Value</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${pvTerminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ FINAL CALCULATION ═══ -->
  <h3>Final Valuation</h3>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Component</th>
          <th>Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>PV of Phase 1 Cash Flows</td>
          <td>${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>PV of Terminal Value</td>
          <td>${pvTerminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>= Enterprise Value</td>
          <td>${enterpriseValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>+ Net Cash (Cash − Debt)</td>
          <td>${netCash.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>= Equity Value</td>
          <td>${equityValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>÷ Shares Outstanding</td>
          <td>{sharesOutstanding.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td>Intrinsic Value Per Share</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${roundedIV.toFixed(2)}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
  <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
  <p>Our base case uses 5% growth and a 9% discount rate. But reasonable people disagree on these numbers. Here's what the intrinsic value looks like under different assumptions.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table class="sensitivity-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{Math.round(g * 100)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{Math.round(row.dr * 100)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>The highlighted cell is our base case. Because 3M carries substantial debt, the intrinsic value is heavily compressed across the entire matrix.</p>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Restructuring Success:</strong> 3M's strategic turnaround and restructuring could generate stronger operational leverage than 5%, leading to higher Free Cash Flow margins.</li>
    <li><strong>Legal Clarity:</strong> If remaining environmental or product liabilities settle for less than expected, massive uncertainty is lifted from the enterprise valuation.</li>
    <li><strong>Pricing Power:</strong> Continued success in offsetting inflation through material price increases.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Ongoing Liabilities:</strong> Additional legal costs tied to "forever chemicals" (PFAS) and Combat Arms earplugs could bleed cash out of the balance sheet for decades.</li>
    <li><strong>Macroeconomic Weakness:</strong> As an industrial cycler, a deep global recession could significantly crater revenue below historical baselines.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt Burden:</strong> Elevated debt levels limit capital flexibility. The company has a significant debt overhang vs. its diminished cash flows.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use DCF instead of a dividend yield approach?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While 3M is famous for its dividend, a DCF focuses on the actual free cash flow generated to pay that dividend and service its significant debt. Relying only on the dividend yield ignores the sustainability of the underlying cash generation and the debt burden.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why 9% discount rate and not 8% or 10%?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The discount rate represents your required return. For a mature, legacy industrial conglomerate with significant litigation overhangs, investors demand a reasonable premium over risk-free assets to compensate for structural uncertainty, without demanding early-stage tech growth premiums.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, tax situation, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

